igated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":12,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":37,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Helbeck was born in 1278, in Warcop, Westmorland, England, her father, Thomas de Helbeck II, was 27 and her mother, Maud de Lucy, was 31. She married Thomas de Warcop I before 1300. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1318, in Warcop, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1278–1318":"1278–1318","1274–1344":"1274–1344","1300–1365":"1300–1365","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1251–1297":"1251–1297","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","before 1300":"enne 1300","1297":"1297","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","Warcop, Westmorland, England":"Warcop, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"1278–1318":"1278–1318","1274–1344":"1274–1344","1300–1365":"1300–1365","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1251–1297":"1251–1297","1248–Female":"1248–Kuollut","before 1300":"ennen vuotta 1300","1297":"1297","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","about 1300":"noin 1300","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","Warcop, Westmorland, England":"Warcop, Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"fr":{"1278–1318":"1278–1318","1274–1344":"1274–1344","1300–1365":"1300–1365","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1251–1297":"1251–1297","1248–Fema